result.execSummary:
This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
10:52 AM Defendant Corey D Yateman in court.  Attorney Justin G Griffis in court for Corey D Yateman.  Prosecuting attorney Alyssa M Jay in court for the State of Wisconsin. 

Defense enters not-guilty plea on all 3 counts of amended complaint and information. Defense acknowledges receipt of amended complaint and information and waives reading. 

Defense requests a date in 30 days. Court sets.
Hearing scheduled for November 14, 2022 at 09:00 am.

10:33 AM Defendant Corey D Yateman in court.  Attorney Justin G Griffis in court for Corey D Yateman.  Prosecuting attorney Zachary A Wittchow in court for the State of Wisconsin. 

The Court conducts a colloquy with the Defense.
The Defendant requests a prelim hearing.
ADA Wittchow states that pretrial offer is now revoked, as it was contingent on waiving the prelim.
The Court conducts a hearing:

Detective William Howrath, of the Waukesha County Sheriff's Department, sworn in and testifies on direct by ADA Wittchow.
Cross examination by attorney Griffis.
The witness is excused and the State rests.
The Defense rests with no testimony proffered.
The Court deems testimony closed.

The State moves for bind over.
The Defense presents closing arguments and requests to dismiss count 2.
The State presents counter arguments.
The Defense present counter arguments.
The Court finds there is not probable cause as it relates to Count 2.
The Court dismisses Count 2.
Court finds probable cause on, Counts 1, 3, & 4, to believe that a felony was committed and binds the defendant over for trial.

The State requests an arraignment date as they will need amend the information.
The Defense does not object.
The Court will adjourn the matter for the Trial Court.
Arraignment scheduled for September 15, 2022 at 10:30 am.
Effective August 1, 2022, this case is assigned to Branch 4, the Honorable Lloyd V. Carter, pursuant to 22-SO-04(67).
Defendant's Demand for Discovery and Inspection.
